<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Ruellia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ruellia dipteracanthus" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dipteracanthus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Ruellia dipteracanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a native of Mexico, but regularly grown as a garden ornamental in warm-temperate and subtropical regions in the world, often under several other names, including 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. squarrosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="squarrosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">R. squarrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. bremeri" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="bremeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">R. bremeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from similar species, based largely on its low, sprawling stature and smaller leaves. This species is increasingly naturalised outside its native range, for instance, in the southern U.S.A. (
<bibRefCitation author="Keith, E" journalOrPublisher="Phytoneuron" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="1 - 3" refId="B6509186" refString="Keith, E, Wright, J, Godwin, W, 2017. Naturalized occurrence of Ruellia dipteracanthus (Acanthaceae) in the USA. Phytoneuron 2017 (57): 1 - 3" title="Naturalized occurrence of Ruellia dipteracanthus (Acanthaceae) in the USA" volume="2017" year="2017">Keith et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
) or in Australia where it is a 
<taxonomicName class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Lemnaceae" genus="Lemna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lemna minor" order="Spathiflorae" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="minor">Lemna minor</taxonomicName>
or emerging environmental weed in south-eastern Queensland and a potential environmental weed or &quot;sleeper weed&quot; in other parts of Australia. It is also considered an invasive species in Japan (
<bibRefCitation author="Mito, T" journalOrPublisher="Global Environmental Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="171 - 191" refId="B6509361" refString="Mito, T, Uesugi, T, 2004. Invasive alien species in Japan: The Status Quo and the new regulation for prevention of their adverse effects. Global Environmental Research 8 (2): 171 - 191" title="Invasive alien species in Japan: The Status Quo and the new regulation for prevention of their adverse effects" volume="8" year="2004">Mito and Uesugi 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
In December 2019, a small population (or a single large clone?) of this species was found sprawling on and at the foot of a damp, steep rock alongside the road (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F6510167" captionText="Figure 9. Ruellia dipteracanthus, Santa Cruz de Tenerife (Igueste de San Andres), December 2019." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e62878.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/494350" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">9</figureCitation>
). The plants most likely escaped from a nearby garden although it was not seen planted in the surroundings.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
Its identification was not straightforward, also because it is not included in garden flora accounts, such as 
<bibRefCitation author="Percy, DM" journalOrPublisher="The European garden flora" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509443" refString="Percy, DM, 2011. . The European garden flora Vol. 5" volume="Vol. 5" year="2011">Percy (2011)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Huxley, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Macmillan, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509172" refString="Huxley, AJ, 1999. The new Royal Horticultural Society dictionary of gardening. Macmillan, London" title="The new Royal Horticultural Society dictionary of gardening" year="1999">Huxley (1999)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Ruellia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ruellia dipteracanthus" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dipteracanthus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Ruellia dipteracanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a low, creeping plant with ovate to narrowly-ovate leaves that are hairy. Its lavender tubular flowers have five small narrow sepals (10-16 mm long) and fruits are glabrous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
This and several other species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Ruellia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ruellia" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Ruellia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are often invasive environmental weeds in the subtropics. These species seed profusely and also reproduce vegetatively via creeping underground stems and stem segments.
</paragraph>
